,"1458":"1458","1403":"1403","1468":"1468","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1531":"1531","1463":"1463","Abt 1458":"about 1458","from 1403 to 1463":"from 1403 to 1463","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Swansea, Glamorgan, Wales":"Swansea, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cradock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh, English:  see  Craddock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craddock","meanings":["Welsh and English: from the Welsh personal name <i>Caradawc</i>, <i>Cradawc</i>, <i>Caradoc</i>, <i>Caradog</i> meaning ‘amiable’, familiar in its Latin form <i>Caractacus</i> (but correctly <i>Caratacus</i>, for British Celtic <i>Caratācos</i>, from the stem <i>carat-</i> ‘dear, love’), a British prince who was taken as prisoner to Rome in about 51  AD  for his leadership of a revolt against the Roman occupation.","Americanized form of German   Gredig  . Compare   Graddick  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Cradock was born from 1403 to 1463, his father, Gwilym Cradock, was 11460 and his mother, Gwenllian Melyn, was 64. He married Jennet Horton in 1468, in Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"from 1403 to 1463–":"1403 kuni 1463–Surnud","1403–Male":"1403–Surnud","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1458–1531":"1458–1531","1463–Male":"1463–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1458":"1458","1403":"1403","1468":"1468","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1531":"1531","1463":"1463","Abt 1458":"umbes 1458","from 1403 to 1463":"1403 kuni 1463","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Swansea, Glamorgan, Wales":"Swansea, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"from 1403 to 1463–":"vuodesta 1403 vuoteen 1463–Kuollut","1403–Male":"1403–Kuollut","1435–Female":"1435–Kuollut","1458–1531":"1458–1531","1463–Male":"1463–Kuollut","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1458":"1458","1403":"1403","1468":"1468","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1531":"1531","1463":"1463","Abt 1458":"noin 1458","from 1403 to 1463":"vuodesta 1403 vuoteen 1463","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Swansea, Glamorgan, Wales":"Swansea, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"from 1403 to 1463–":"du 1403 au 1463–Décédé","1403–Male":"1403–Décédé","1435–Female":"1435–Décédée","1458–1531":"1458–1531","1463–Male":"1463–Décédé","1400–Female":"1400–Décédée","1458":"1458","1403":"1403","1468":"1468","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1531":"1531","1463":"1463","Abt 1458":"environ 1458","from 